post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_16530970_16530970_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.5833333333333334, "section_id": 5403}}, "n3337": {"so_16530970_16530970_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.5833333333333334, "section_id": 5198}}, "n4659": {"so_16530970_16530970_1": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.5833333333333334, "section_id": 6852}}}, "16530970": {"ViewCount": "462", "Body": "<p>What does the following means?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_16530970_16530970_0\"><strong>ISO/IEC 14882:2011</strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_16530970_16530970_1\">7.1.2 Function specifiers [dcl.fct.spec]\n  ...<br>\n  3 ... The inline specifier shall not appear on a block scope function\n  declaration.</br></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Is smth like this is invalid according to this quote or not?</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nint main()\n{\n    inline void foo();\n    foo();\n}\n\nvoid foo()\n{\n    std::cout &lt;&lt; \"::foo() \\n\";\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>gcc compiles it without any error.</p>\n<p>Am i wrong or not?</p>\n", "Title": "inline in block scope function declaration", "CreationDate": "2013-05-13T20:54:28.103", "LastActivityDate": "2013-05-13T21:14:43.623", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2013-05-13T21:14:43.623", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "6271971", "Id": "16530970", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1608835", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "16531115": {"Id": "16531115", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>I think <code>gcc</code> is tricking itself here. This should be illegal. What is happening here is <code>gcc</code> adds <code>inline void foo();</code> to its symbol table and <strong>considers it undefined</strong>. So the call <code>foo();</code> should be undefined as far as it is concerned. </p>\n<p>However when the linker (<code>ld</code>) later tries to link the code it finds the definition of the <code>foo</code> in global scope which is reachable and uses that instead.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-05-13T21:04:21.147", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-05-13T21:04:21.147", "ParentId": "16530970", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "6271971"}, "16531104": {"Id": "16531104", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_16530970_16531104_0\">Is smth like this is invalid according to this quote or not?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, it is in invalid because of the Standard paragraph you quote in the question's text. </p>\n<p>The fact that the compiler accepts it may either be a bug or a documented extension, but is definitely not conforming to the C++11 Standard.</p>\n<p><em>Additional information:</em></p>\n<p>When I try to compile the above program with GCC 4.7.2, I get a warning that says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_16530970_16531104_1\">warning: <code>'inline'</code> specifier invalid for function <code>'foo'</code> declared out of global scope [<code>-pedantic</code>]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1932150", "LastActivityDate": "2013-05-13T21:09:42.650", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2013-05-13T21:03:52.917", "ParentId": "16530970", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1932150", "LastEditDate": "2013-05-13T21:09:42.650"}});